.TH "regulator_get_hardware_vsel_register" 9 "regulator_get_hardware_vsel_register" "May 2021" "Kernel Hacker's Manual" LINUX
.SH NAME
regulator_get_hardware_vsel_register \- get the HW voltage selector register
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B "int" regulator_get_hardware_vsel_register
.BI "(struct regulator *regulator "  ","
.BI "unsigned *vsel_reg "  ","
.BI "unsigned *vsel_mask "  ");"
.SH ARGUMENTS
.IP "regulator" 12
regulator source
.IP "vsel_reg" 12
voltage selector register, output parameter
.IP "vsel_mask" 12
mask for voltage selector bitfield, output parameter
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
Returns the hardware register offset and bitmask used for setting the
regulator voltage. This might be useful when configuring voltage-scaling
hardware or firmware that can make I2C requests behind the kernel's back,
for example.

On success, the output parameters \fIvsel_reg\fP and \fIvsel_mask\fP are filled in
and 0 is returned, otherwise a negative errno is returned.
